  Findings

  No backdoors, hardcoded credentials, or embedded secrets were found in what I examined. Specifically I ruled out the items that first
  looked suspicious:

  - CSME Kernel Root Key / EFW User root Key / PG Key for SRAM / EFW Manifest Key (at 0xfe021920, 0xfe2c8800) are labels in Intel ME 
  partition manifest metadata, followed by what are public-key hashes, not private key material. This is normal ME secure-boot bookkeeping,
  not a leaked secret. Neither has any code xref.
  - UEFI Crypto Library default seed (%ld) (0xff614184) is the OpenSSL DRBG personalization string, sitting in a table next to algorithm
  names (RSA-SHA1, Nonce, MD5…). The image uses OpenSSL's SP800-90A CTR/HASH-DRBG; on this Intel platform entropy comes from RDRAND/RDSEED,
  so this is standard EDK2 behavior, not the old constant-seed weakness. No instruction embeds the string's address.
  - secureShellClient/Server, challengePassword, userPassword, master secret, etc. are all standard OpenSSL X.509/TLS OID and label strings
  — not authentication logic.
  - The password / INTEL TOKEN / OEM TOKEN / Privileged ... Debug Enabled / MEBxPassword strings live in Fpt.efi and are the tool's
  documented features for reporting/writing debug tokens, FPFs, and MEBx state — not a covert channel.

  The real risk here is what the pair represents, not a hidden flaw. A full writable SPI image plus the Intel flash programmer together
  form a complete firmware-reflashing kit: with Fpt.efi (or a modified 1.bin) one can rewrite a Meteor Lake machine's BIOS and ME regions,
  manipulate Boot Guard / debug-authorization fuses (FPFs), write INTEL/OEM debug tokens, and set the MEBx password. That capability is
  legitimate for firmware engineering but is exactly what you'd want to keep access-controlled.

